==SI units==
The base unit of length in the SI system is the '''metre'''. This has had several definitions over time:
;1889 :The [[w:BIPM|International Bureau of Weights and Measures]] defines the metre as the distance between two marks on a platinum-iridium alloy bar (the [[:w:International Prototype Metre|International Prototype Metre]]). This prototype is kept in a vault in Sèvres, near Paris. ;1960 :The 11th [[w:CPGM|General Conference on Weights and Measures]]<ref> {{cite book | editor = [[:w:CPGM|Conférence Générale des Poids es Mesures]] | title = Compte rendu des séances de la 11<sup>e</sup> Conférence générale des Poids es Mesures | year = 1960 | publisher = Gauthier-Villars | location = Paris | pages = 85 }} </ref> redefines the metre in terms of a specific number of wavelengths of light of a specific frequency in a vacuum. It is defined to be 1&thinsp;650&thinsp;763.7'''3''' wavelengths of the electromagnetic radiation emitted by an electron transitioning between the levels 2p<sub>10</sub> and 5d<sub>5</sub> of the krypton-86 (<sup>86</sup>Kr) atom in a vacuum. The metre is now defined in terms of reproducible physical effects, rather than a synthetic artifact. ;1983 :The 17th General Conference on Weights and Measures<ref> {{cite book | editor = Conférence Générale des Poids es Mesures | title = Compte rendu des séances de la 13<sup>e</sup> Conférence générale des Poids es Mesures | year = 1983 }} </ref> redefines the metre in terms of the distance traversed by light (having a universally constant speed in a vacuum) in a specific time. It is defined as the distance traveled by a beam of light in a vacuum in 1/299&thinsp;792&thinsp;45'''8''' [[Units of measurement/Time|second]]. This is the current definition. This has the effect that the speed of light is defined to be exactly 299&thinsp;792&thinsp;45'''8''' m/s.
{| class=wikitable style="text-align:center; margin: 1em auto 1em auto" width=400 |- |+Conversion of metric units of length<ref>After {{cite book | editor = Diem, K., Lentner, C. (ed.) | title = Documenta Geigy Scientific Tables | edition = 7th ed. | year = 1970 | publisher = J.R. Geigy S.A. | location = Basle '''Bold text'''| chapter = Physics | pages = 200 }} </ref> |- !colspan=2|A |rowspan=10| !colspan=7|B |- |'''Unit'''||'''Symbol''' |'''pm''' |'''nm''' |'''μm''' |'''mm''' |'''cm''' |style="border-left:1px solid black;"|'''m''' |style="border-left:1px solid black;"|'''km''' |- |picometre |pm |<sup>&nbsp;</sup>1<sup>&nbsp;</sup> |10<sup>-3</sup> |10<sup>-6</sup> |10<sup>-9</sup> |10<sup>-10</sup> |style="border-left:1px solid black;"|10<sup>-12</sup> |style="border-left:1px solid black;"|10<sup>-15</sup> |- |ångström<sup>†</sup> |Å |10<sup>2</sup> |10<sup>&minus;1</sup> |10<sup>&minus;4</sup> |10<sup>&minus;7</sup> |10<sup>&minus;8</sup> |style="border-left:1px solid black;"|10<sup>&minus;10</sup> |style="border-left:1px solid black;"|10<sup>&minus;13</sup> |- |nanometre |nm |10<sup>3</sup> |<sup>&nbsp;</sup>1<sup>&nbsp;</sup> |10<sup>&minus;3</sup> |10<sup>&minus;6</sup> |10<sup>&minus;7</sup> |style="border-left:1px solid black;"|10<sup>&minus;9</sup> |style="border-left:1px solid black;"|10<sup>&minus;12</sup> |- |micrometre |μm |10<sup>6</sup> |10<sup>3</sup> |<sup>&nbsp;</sup>1<sup>&nbsp;</sup> |10<sup>&minus;3</sup> |10<sup>&minus;4</sup> |style="border-left:1px solid black;"|10<sup>&minus;6</sup> |style="border-left:1px solid black;"|10<sup>&minus;9</sup> |- |millimetre |mm |10<sup>9</sup> |10<sup>6</sup> |10<sup>3</sup> |<sup>&nbsp;</sup>1<sup>&nbsp;</sup> |10<sup>&minus;1</sup> |style="border-left:1px solid black;"|10<sup>&minus;3</sup> |style="border-left:1px solid black;"|10<sup>&minus;6</sup> |- |centimetre |cm |10<sup>10</sup> |10<sup>7</sup> |10<sup>4</sup> |10<sup>1</sup> |<sup>&nbsp;</sup>1<sup>&nbsp;</sup> |style="border-left:1px solid black;"|10<sup>&minus;2</sup> |style="border-left:1px solid black;"|10<sup>&minus;5</sup> |- |style="border-top:1px solid black;"|metre |style="border-top:1px solid black;"|m |style="border-top:1px solid black;"|10<sup>12</sup> |style="border-top:1px solid black;"|10<sup>9</sup> |style="border-top:1px solid black;"|10<sup>6</sup> |style="border-top:1px solid black;"|10<sup>3</sup> |style="border-top:1px solid black;"|10<sup>2</sup> |style="border-top:1px solid black; border-left:1px solid black;"|<sup>&nbsp;</sup>1<sup>&nbsp;</sup> |style="border-top:1px solid black; border-left:1px solid black;"|10<sup>3</sup> |- |style="border-top:1px solid black;"|kilometre |style="border-top:1px solid black;"|km |style="border-top:1px solid black;"|10<sup>15</sup> |style="border-top:1px solid black;"|10<sup>12</sup> |style="border-top:1px solid black;"|10<sup>9</sup> |style="border-top:1px solid black;"|10<sup>6</sup> |style="border-top:1px solid black;"|10<sup>5</sup> |style="border-top:1px solid black; border-left:1px solid black;"|10<sup>3</sup> |style="border-top:1px solid black; border-left:1px solid black;"|<sup>&nbsp;</sup>1<sup>&nbsp;</sup> |- |colspan=10 style="font-size:88%" align=left| :*1 '''A''' unit = ''b'' '''B''' units (b given in the table) :*<sup>†</sup> Ångström is accepted for use with, but not defined by the SI system. Its use is officially discouraged by the [[:w:CIPM|CIPM]]. |}
