== Limits And Continuity ==

Evaluate the following limits.
{{question-answer|question=180. <math>\displaystyle\lim_{(x,y)\rightarrow(1,-2)}\frac{y^2+2xy}{y+2x}</math>|answer={{noprint|1= −2}}}}
{{question-answer|question=181. <math>\displaystyle\lim_{(x,y)\rightarrow(4,5)}\frac{\sqrt{x+y}-3}{x+y-9}</math>|answer={{noprint|1= 1/6}}}}

At what points is the function ''f'' continuous?

{{question-answer|question=182. <math>f(x,y) = \ln|x-y|</math>|answer={{noprint|1= <math>\{(x,y)\mid x\neq y\}</math>}}}}
{{question-answer|question=183. <math>f(x,y) = \displaystyle\frac{\ln(x^2 + y^2)}{x-y+1}</math>|answer={{noprint|1= All points (''x'',''y'') except for (0,0) and the line ''y''=''x''+1}}}}

Use the two-path test to show that the following limits do not exist. (A path does not have to be a straight line.) 

{{question-answer|question=184. <math>\displaystyle\lim_{(x,y)\rightarrow(0,0)}\frac{4xy}{3x^2+y^2}</math>|answer={{noprint|1= The limit is 1 along the line ''y''=''x'', and −1 along the line ''y''=−''x''}}}}
{{question-answer|question=185. <math>\displaystyle\lim_{(x,y)\rightarrow(0,0)}\frac{y}{\sqrt{x^2-y^2}}</math>|answer={{noprint|1= The limit is 0 along the line ''y''=0, and <math>1/\sqrt 3</math> along the line ''x''=2''y''}}}}
{{question-answer|question=186. <math>\displaystyle\lim_{(x,y)\rightarrow(0,0)}\frac{x^3-y^2}{x^3+y^2}</math>|answer={{noprint|1= The limit is 1 along the line ''y''=0, and −1 along the line ''x''=0}}}}
{{question-answer|question=187. <math>\displaystyle\lim_{(x,y)\rightarrow(0,0)}\frac{x^2y^2+y^6}{x^3}</math>|answer={{noprint|1= The limit is 0 along any line of the form ''y''=''mx'', and 2 along the parabola <math>x=y^2</math>}}}}

== Partial Derivatives ==

{{question-answer|question=200. Find <math>\partial z / \partial x</math> if <math>\displaystyle z(x,y) = \frac1{\ln(xy)}</math>|answer={{noprint|1= <math>\frac{-1}{x(\ln(xy))^2}</math>}}}}
{{question-answer|question=201. Find all three partial derivatives of the function <math>\displaystyle f(x,y,z) = xe^{y^2 + z}</math>|answer={{noprint|1= <math>\displaystyle f_x=e^{y^2+z},\ f_y=2xye^{y^2+z},\ f_z=f.</math>}}}}

Find the four second partial derivatives of the following functions.

{{question-answer|question=202. <math>f(x,y) = \cos(xy)</math>|answer={{noprint|1= <math>f_{xx}=-y^2\cos(xy),\ f_{yy} = -x^2\cos(xy),\ f_{xy} = f_{yx} = -\sin(xy) -xy\cos(xy).</math>}}}}
{{question-answer|question=203. <math>f(x,y) = xe^y</math>|answer={{noprint|1= <math>f_{xx}=0,\ f_{yy} = xe^y,\ f_{xy} = f_{yx} = e^y.</math>}}}}

== Chain Rule ==

Find <math>df/dt.</math>

{{question-answer|question=220. <math>f(x,y) = x^2y-xy^3,\ x(t) = t^2,\ y(t) = t^{-2}</math>|answer={{noprint|1= <math>2t+4t^{-5}</math>}}}}
{{question-answer|question=221. <math>f(x,y) = \sqrt{x^2+y^2},\ x(t) = \cos(2t),\ y(t) = \sin(2t)</math>|answer={{noprint|1= 0}}}}
{{question-answer|question=222. <math>\displaystyle f(x,y,z) = \frac{x-y}{y+z},\ x(t) = t,\ \displaystyle y(t) = 2t,\ z(t) = 3t</math>|answer={{noprint|1= 0}}}}

Find <math>f_s,\ f_t.</math>

{{question-answer|question=223. <math>f(x,y) = \sin(x)\cos(2y),\ x=s+t,\ y=s-t</math>|answer={{noprint|1= <math>f_s = \cos(s+t)\cos(2s-2t) - 2\sin(s+t)\sin(2s-2t)\\ f_t = \cos(s+t)\cos(2s-2t) + 2\sin(s+t)\sin(2s-2t)</math>}}}}
{{question-answer|question=224. <math>\displaystyle f(x,y,z) = \frac{x-z}{y+z},\ x(t)=s+t,\ y(t)=st,\ z(t)=s-t</math>|answer={{noprint|1= <math>\displaystyle f_s = \frac{-2t(t+1)}{(st+s-t)^2}\\ \displaystyle f_t = \frac{2s}{(st+s-t)^2}</math>}}}}


{{question-answer|question=225. The volume of a pyramid with a square base is <math>V = \frac13x^2h</math>, where ''x'' is the side of the square base and ''h'' is the height of the pyramid. Suppose that <math>\displaystyle x(t) = \frac t{t+1}</math> and <math>\displaystyle h(t) = \frac1{t+1}</math> for <math>t\geq 0.</math> Find <math>V'(t).</math>|answer={{noprint|1= <math>\displaystyle \frac{2t-t^2}{3(t+1)^4}</math>}}}}

