== Double Integrals over General Regions ==

Evaluate the following integrals.

{{question-answer|question=300. <math>\displaystyle\iint_R xy dA,</math> ''R'' is bounded by ''x''=0, ''y''=2''x''+1, and ''y''=5−2''x''.|answer={{noprint|1= <math>2</math>}}}}
{{question-answer|question=301. <math>\displaystyle\iint_R (x+y) dA,</math> ''R'' is in the first quadrant and bounded by ''x''=0, <math>y=x^2,</math> and <math>y=8 - x^2.</math>|answer={{noprint|1= <math>152/3</math>}}}}

Use double integrals to compute the volume of the given region.

{{question-answer|question=302. The solid in the first octant bound by the coordinate planes and the surface <math>z = 8-x^2-2y^2. </math>|answer={{noprint|1= <math>4\pi\sqrt2</math>}}}}
{{question-answer|question=303. The solid beneath the cylinder <math>z=y^2</math> and above the region <math>R = \{(x,y)\mid y\in[0,1],\ x\in[y,1]\}.</math>|answer={{noprint|1= <math>1/12</math>}}}}
{{question-answer|question=304. The solid bounded by the paraboloids <math>z=x^2+y^2</math> and <math>z = 50-x^2-y^2.</math>|answer={{noprint|1= <math>625\pi</math>}}}}

== Double Integrals in Polar Coordinates ==

{{question-answer|question=320. Evaluate <math>\displaystyle\iint_R 2xy dA</math> for <math>R=\{(r,\theta)\mid r\in[1,3],\ \theta\in[0,\pi/2]\}</math>|answer={{noprint|1= <math>20</math>}}}}
{{question-answer|question=321. Find the average value of the function <math>f(r,\theta) = 1/r^2</math> over the region <math>\{(r,\theta)\mid r\in[2,4]\}.</math>|answer={{noprint|1= <math>\displaystyle\frac{\ln2}6</math>}}}}
{{question-answer|question=322. Evaluate <math>\displaystyle\int_0^3\int_0^{\sqrt{9-x^2}} \sqrt{x^2+y^2}dydx.</math>|answer={{noprint|1= <math>9\pi/2</math>}}}}
{{question-answer|question=323. Evaluate <math>\displaystyle\iint_R \frac{x-y}{x^2+y^2+1}dA</math> if ''R'' is the unit disk centered at the origin.|answer={{noprint|1= <math>0</math>}}}}

== Triple Integrals ==

{{question-answer|question=340. Evaluate <math>\displaystyle\int_1^{\ln 8}\int_0^{\ln 4}\int_0^{\ln 2} e^{-x-y-2z}dxdydz.</math>|answer={{noprint|1= <math>\displaystyle\frac3{16}\left(e^{-2}-8^{-2}\right)</math>}}}}

In the following exercises, sketching the region of integration may be helpful.

{{question-answer|question=341. Find the volume of the solid in the first octant bounded by the plane 2''x''+3''y''+6''z''=12 and the coordinate planes.|answer={{noprint|1= <math>8</math>}}}}
{{question-answer|question=342. Find the volume of the solid in the first octant bounded by the cylinder <math>z=\sin(y)</math> for <math>y\in[0,\pi]</math>, and the planes ''y''=''x'' and ''x''=0.|answer={{noprint|1= <math>\pi</math>}}}}
{{question-answer|question=343. Evaluate <math>\displaystyle\int_0^1\int_y^{2-y}\int_0^{2-x-y} xydzdxdy.</math>|answer={{noprint|1= <math>2/15</math>}}}}
{{question-answer|question=344. Rewrite the integral <math>\displaystyle\int_0^1\int_{-2}^2\int_0^{\sqrt{4-y^2}}dzdydx</math> in the order ''dydzdx''.|answer={{noprint|1= <math>\displaystyle\int_0^1\int_0^2\int_{-\sqrt{4-z^2}}^{\sqrt{4-z^2}}dydzdx </math>}}}}

== Cylindrical And Spherical Coordinates ==

{{question-answer|question=360. Evaluate the integral in cylindrical coordinates: <math>\displaystyle\int_0^3\int_{0}^{\sqrt{9-x^2}}\int_0^{\sqrt{x^2+y^2}}\frac1{\sqrt{x^2+y^2}}dzdydx</math>|answer={{noprint|1= <math>9\pi/4</math>}}}}
{{question-answer|question=361. Find the mass of the solid cylinder <math>D = \{(r,\theta,z)\mid r\in[0,3],\ z\in[0,2]\}</math> given the density function <math>\delta(r,\theta,z) = 5e^{-r^2}</math>|answer={{noprint|1= <math>10\pi(1-e^{-9})</math>}}}}
{{question-answer|question=362. Use a triple integral to find the volume of the region bounded by the plane ''z''=0 and the hyperboloid <math>z = \sqrt{17} - \sqrt{1+x^2+y^2}</math>|answer={{noprint|1= <math>\displaystyle\frac{2\pi(1+7\sqrt{17})}{3}</math>}}}}
{{question-answer|question=363. If ''D'' is a unit ball, use a triple integral in spherical coordinates to evaluate <math>\iiint_D(x^2+y^2+z^2)^{5/2}dV</math>|answer={{noprint|1= <math>\pi/2</math>}}}}
{{question-answer|question=364. Find the mass of a solid cone <math>\{(\rho,\phi,\theta)\mid \phi\leq\pi/3,\ z\in[0,4]\}</math> if the density function is <math>\delta(\rho,\phi,\theta) = 5-z</math>|answer={{noprint|1= <math>128\pi</math>}}}}
{{question-answer|question=365. Find the volume of the region common to two cylinders: <math>x^2+z^2 = 1,\ y^2+z^2 = 1</math>|answer={{noprint|1= <math>16/3</math>}}}}

== Center of Mass and Centroid ==

{{question-answer|question=380. Find the center of mass for three particles located in space at (1,2,3), (0,0,1), and (1,1,0), with masses 2, 1, and 1 respectively. |answer={{noprint|1= <math>\frac{\langle 3,5,7\rangle}{4}</math>}}}}
{{question-answer|question=381. Find the center of mass for a piece of wire with the density <math>\rho(x) = 1+\sin(x)</math> for <math>x\in[0,\pi].</math>|answer={{noprint|1= <math>\pi/2</math>}}}}
{{question-answer|question=382. Find the center of mass for a piece of wire with the density <math>\rho(x) = 2-x^2/16</math> for <math>x\in[0,4].</math>|answer={{noprint|1= <math>9/5</math>}}}}
{{question-answer|question=383. Find the centroid of the region in the first quadrant bounded by the coordinate axes and <math>x^2+y^2=16.</math>|answer={{noprint|1= <math>\left(\frac{16}{3\pi},\frac{16}{3\pi}\right)</math>}}}}
{{question-answer|question=384. Find the centroid of the region in the first quadrant bounded by <math>y=\ln(x)</math>, <math>y=0</math>, and <math>x=e</math>.|answer={{noprint|1= <math>((e^2+1)/4, e/2 - 1)</math>}}}}
{{question-answer|question=385. Find the center of mass for the region <math>\{(x,y)\mid x\in[0,4], y\in[0,2]\}</math>, with the density <math>\rho(x,y) = 1+x/2.</math>|answer={{noprint|1= <math>(7/3, 1)</math>}}}}
{{question-answer|question=386. Find the center of mass for the triangular plate with vertices (0,0), (0,4), and (4,0), with density <math>\rho(x,y) = 1+x+y.</math>|answer={{noprint|1= <math>(16/11, 16/11)</math>}}}}

== Vector Fields ==

One can sketch two-dimensional vector fields by plotting vector values, flow curves, and/or equipotential curves.

{{question-answer|question=401. Find and sketch the gradient field <math>\mathbf F = \nabla\phi</math> for the potential function <math>\phi(x,y) = \sqrt{x^2+y^2}</math>.
|answer={{noprint|1= <math>\mathbf F = \left\langle\frac x{\sqrt{x^2+y^2}},\frac y{\sqrt{x^2+y^2}}\right\rangle</math>
[[File:Radial vector field.svg|thumb|none|]]}}}}

{{question-answer|question=402. Find and sketch the gradient field <math>\mathbf F = \nabla\phi</math> for the potential function <math>\phi(x,y) = \sin(x)\sin(y)</math> for <math>|x|\leq\pi</math> and <math>|y|\leq\pi</math>.
|answer={{noprint|1= <math>\nabla\phi(x,y) = \langle \cos(x)\sin(y), \sin(x)\cos(y)\rangle</math>}}}}

{{question-answer|question=403. Find the gradient field <math>\mathbf F = \nabla\phi</math> for the potential function <math>\phi(x,y,z) = e^{-z}\sin(x+y)</math>
|answer={{noprint|1= <math>\mathbf F = e^{-z}\left\langle \cos(x+y), \cos(x+y), -\sin(x+y)\right\rangle</math>}}}}

== Line Integrals ==

{{question-answer|question=420. Evaluate <math>\int_C(x^2+y^2)ds</math> if ''C'' is the line segment from (0,0) to (5,5)|answer={{noprint|1= <math>\frac{250\sqrt2}3</math>}}}}
{{question-answer|question=421. Evaluate <math>\int_C(x^2+y^2)ds</math> if ''C'' is the circle of radius 4 centered at the origin|answer={{noprint|1= <math>128\pi</math>}}}}
{{question-answer|question=422. Evaluate <math>\int_C(y-z)ds</math> if ''C'' is the helix <math>\mathbf r(t) = \langle 3\cos(t),3\sin(t),t\rangle,\ t\in[0,2\pi]</math>|answer={{noprint|1= <math>-2\sqrt{10}\pi^2</math>}}}}
{{question-answer|question=423. Evaluate <math>\int_C \mathbf F\cdot d\mathbf r</math> if <math>\mathbf F =\langle x,y\rangle</math> and ''C'' is the arc of the parabola <math>\mathbf r(t) = \langle 4t,t^2\rangle,\ t\in[0,1]</math>|answer={{noprint|1= <math>17/2</math>}}}}
{{question-answer|question=424. Find the work required to move an object from (1,1,1) to (8,4,2) along a straight line in the force field <math>\displaystyle\mathbf F = \frac{\langle x,y,z\rangle}{x^2+y^2+z^2} </math>|answer={{noprint|1= <math>\ln(2\sqrt7)</math>}}}}

== Conservative Vector Fields ==

Determine if the following vector fields are conservative on <math>\mathbb R^2.</math>

{{question-answer|question=440. <math>\langle -y, x+y \rangle</math>|answer={{noprint|1= No}}}}
{{question-answer|question=441. <math>\langle 2x^3+xy^2, 2y^3+x^2y\rangle</math>|answer={{noprint|1= Yes}}}}

Determine if the following vector fields are conservative on their respective domains in <math>\mathbb R^3.</math> When possible, find the potential function.

{{question-answer|question=442. <math>\langle y,x,1\rangle </math>|answer={{noprint|1= <math>\phi(x,y,z)=xy+z</math>}}}}
{{question-answer|question=443. <math>\langle x^3,2y,-z^3 \rangle</math>|answer={{noprint|1= <math>\phi(x,y,z)=(x^4+4y^2-z^4)/4</math>}}}}

== Green's Theorem ==

{{question-answer|question=460. Evaluate the circulation of the field <math>\mathbf F=\langle 2xy,x^2-y^2\rangle</math> over the boundary of the region above ''y''=0 and below ''y''=''x''(2-''x'') in two different ways, and compare the answers.|answer={{noprint|1= <math>0</math>}}}}
{{question-answer|question=461. Evaluate the circulation of the field <math>\mathbf F=\langle 0,x^2+y^2\rangle</math> over the unit circle centered at the origin in two different ways, and compare the answers.|answer={{noprint|1= <math>0 </math>}}}}
{{question-answer|question=462. Evaluate the flux of the field <math>\mathbf F=\langle y,-x\rangle</math> over the square with vertices (0,0), (1,0), (1,1), and (0,1) in two different ways, and compare the answers.|answer={{noprint|1= <math>0 </math>}}}}

== Divergence And Curl ==

{{question-answer|question=480. Find the divergence of <math>\langle 2x, 4y, -3z\rangle</math>
|answer={{noprint|1= <math>3</math>}}}}

{{question-answer|question=481. Find the divergence of <math>\displaystyle\frac{\langle x,y,z\rangle}{1+x^2+y^2}</math>
|answer={{noprint|1= <math> \displaystyle\frac{x^2+y^2+3}{(1+x^2+y^2)^2}</math>}}}}

{{question-answer|question=482. Find the curl of <math>\langle x^2-y^2, xy, z\rangle</math>
|answer={{noprint|1= <math>\langle 0,0,3y\rangle</math>}}}}

{{question-answer|question=483. Find the curl of <math>\langle z^2\sin(y), xz^2\cos(y), 2xz\sin(y)\rangle</math>
|answer={{noprint|1= <math>\mathbf 0 </math>}}}}

{{question-answer|question=484. Prove that the general rotation field <math>\mathbf F = \mathbf a\times\mathbf r</math>, where <math>\mathbf a</math> is a non-zero constant vector and <math>\mathbf r = \langle x,y,z\rangle</math>, has zero divergence, and the curl of <math>\mathbf F</math> is <math>2\mathbf a</math>.
|answer={{noprint|1= If <math>\mathbf a = \langle a_1,a_2,a_3\rangle</math>, then

<math>\mathbf F = \mathbf a \times \mathbf r = \langle a_2z-a_3y, a_3x-a_1z, a_1y-a_2x\rangle = \langle f,g,h\rangle</math>, and then

<math>\nabla\cdot\mathbf F = \mathbf f_x + \mathbf g_y + \mathbf h_z = 0+0+0=0,</math>

<math>\nabla\times \mathbf F = \langle h_y - g_z, f_z-h_x, g_x-f_y\rangle
= \langle a_1 + a_1, a_2+a_2, a_3+a_3\rangle = 2\mathbf a.</math>}}}}

== Surface Integrals ==

{{question-answer|question=500. Give a parametric description of the plane <math>2x-4y+3z=16.</math>|answer={{noprint|1= <math>\langle u,v,(16-2u+4v)/3\rangle,\ u,v\in\mathbb R</math>}}}}
{{question-answer|question=501. Give a parametric description of the hyperboloid <math>z^2=1+x^2+y^2.</math>|answer={{noprint|1= <math>\langle\sqrt{v^2-1}\cos(u),\sqrt{v^2-1}\sin(u),v\rangle,\ u\in[0,2\pi],\ |v|\geq1</math>}}}}
{{question-answer|question=502. Integrate <math>f(x,y,z) = xy</math> over the portion of the plane ''z''=2−''x''−''y'' in the first octant. |answer={{noprint|1= <math>2/\sqrt3</math>}}}}
{{question-answer|question=503. Integrate <math>f(x,y,z) = x^2 + y^2</math> over the paraboloid <math>z=x^2+y^2,\ z\in[0,4].</math>|answer={{noprint|1= <math>\frac{(391\sqrt{17} + 1)\pi}{60}</math>}}}}
{{question-answer|question=504. Find the flux of the field <math>\mathbf F = \langle x,y,z\rangle</math> across the surface of the cone
:<math>z^2=x^2+y^2, \ z\in[0,1],</math>
with normal vectors pointing in the positive ''z'' direction.|answer={{noprint|1= <math>0</math>}}}}
{{question-answer|question=505. Find the flux of the field <math>\mathbf F = \langle -y,z,1\rangle</math> across the surface
:<math>y=x^2, \ z\in[0,4],\ x\in[0,1],</math>
with normal vectors pointing in the positive ''y'' direction.|answer={{noprint|1= <math>-10</math>}}}}

== Stokes' Theorem ==

{{question-answer|question=520. Use a surface integral to evaluate the circulation of the field <math>\mathbf F = \langle x^2 - z^2, y, 2xz \rangle</math> on the boundary of the plane <math>z = 4-x-y</math> in the first octant. |answer={{noprint|1= <math>\frac{-128}{3}</math>}}}}
{{question-answer|question=521. Use a surface integral to evaluate the circulation of the field <math>\mathbf F = \langle y^2,-z^2,x \rangle</math> on the circle <math>\mathbf r(t) = \langle 3\cos(t),4\cos(t),5\sin(t) \rangle.</math>|answer={{noprint|1= <math>15\pi</math>}}}}
{{question-answer|question=522. Use a line integral to find <math>\iint_S(\nabla\times F)\cdot\mathbf n dS</math> <br /> where <math> \mathbf F = \langle x,y,z \rangle</math>, <math>S</math> is the upper half of the ellipsoid <math> \frac{x^2}4 + \frac{y^2}9 + z^2 = 1 </math>, and <math>\mathbf n</math> points in the direction of the ''z''-axis. |answer={{noprint|1= <math>0</math>}}}}
{{question-answer|question=523. Use a line integral to find <math>\iint_S(\nabla\times F)\cdot\mathbf n dS</math> <br /> where <math> \mathbf F = \langle 2y,-z,x-y-z \rangle</math>, <math>S</math> is the part of the sphere <math> x^2 + y^2 + z^2 = 25 </math> for <math>3 \leq z \leq 5</math>, and <math>\mathbf n</math> points in the direction of the ''z''-axis.|answer={{noprint|1= <math>-32\pi</math>}}}}

